README — EuroEdu Analytics Center · Data Warehouse & Business Intelligence
Project Objective
This project develops a Business Intelligence solution based on a Data Warehouse model to analyse gender parity in European higher education between 2013 and 2023, using public Eurostat/PORDATA data on enrolled students by year, country, gender, study cycle and field of education.

The solution allows to:

Assess the degree of gender parity in European higher education.

Compare countries, study cycles and fields of education.

Analyse the temporal evolution of parity over the decade.

Support institutional and policy decisions with robust indicators.
​

Context
Fictional organisation: EuroEdu Analytics Center, a data analytics centre focused on education and social equality.
​

Data source: PORDATA/Eurostat — higher education students by sex, study cycle and field of education (latest update 15‑09‑2025).

Analysis period: 2013–2023.
​

Unit of analysis: number of students by Year, Country, Gender, Study Cycle and Field of Education.

The full project report is written in Portuguese and is available in this repository as a PDF.

Fact Table Structure
The dimensional model uses a single fact table with the following structure:

Year (2013–2023)

Country (European countries in scope)

Gender (Male, Female)

Study Cycle (Short Cycle, Bachelor, Master, Doctorate)

Field of Education (PORDATA/Eurostat categories)

Number of Students (central quantitative measure)

Each row represents a unique combination of these dimensions, allowing the same metric (Number of Students) to be analysed across temporal, geographic, academic and gender perspectives.

Methodology and Workflow
The process started with extracting data from PORDATA/Eurostat in CSV format, containing aggregated records by year, country, gender, study cycle, field of education and number of enrolled students. The CSV file was converted to Excel (.xlsx) and transformed into a structured table, which facilitated initial cleaning and normalisation of headers and text values (for example, aligning names like CiclodeEstudo and removing extra spaces).

Next, the Excel file was imported into Power BI, using Power Query to complete the ETL process (Extract, Transform, Load). At this stage, data types were checked and adjusted, missing values in “Number of Students” were handled through DAX measures (instead of deleting rows), duplicates were removed and consistency of Year, Country, Gender, Study Cycle and Field of Education was ensured.
​

After ETL, the fact table FactEnsinoSuperior was built, with granularity at the level of Year, Country, Gender, Study Cycle and Field of Education, having Number of Students as the central measure. From this table, several DAX measures were created for the main indicators: total students, total males, total females, gender percentages, absolute and percentage difference between genders, and the GPI (Gender Parity Index), ensuring that all calculations adapt dynamically to filters applied in the reports.

With the data model validated, multiple Power BI dashboards were created, organised by theme: overview of global KPIs, comparative analysis by country, analysis by study cycle, analysis by field of education and temporal trends. Each page uses bar charts, maps, rankings and interactive slicers to enable flexible exploration of the data while keeping a simple, coherent and insight‑oriented design.
​

Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)
Global KPIs — Overall State of Parity
High‑level view of gender distribution in European higher education:
​

Total Students

Total Male Students

Total Female Students

Male Percentage

Female Percentage

Percentage Difference Between Genders

These indicators show whether there is near 50/50 balance or relevant deviations towards one gender.
​

Comparative KPIs — Where Are the Gaps?
Analyse differences between specific categories:
​

Male/Female percentage by Country

Male/Female percentage by Study Cycle

Male/Female percentage by Field of Education

They help identify whether deviations are:

Cultural (country‑related)

Structural (level/cycle‑related)

Vocational (field‑related)
​

Temporal KPIs — How Did Parity Evolve?
Measure how parity changes over time:
​

Annual variation in female percentage

Annual variation in male percentage

These KPIs show whether gender parity is improving, stable or declining over the last decade.
​

Contribution KPIs — Who Drives the European Totals?
Assess each country’s weight in total European enrolments:
​

Male contribution by Country

Female contribution by Country

They highlight countries with greater statistical influence (for example, Germany, France, Italy, Spain).

Data Model (DW/BI)
Conceptual Model — Star Schema
The model follows a star schema with one central fact table and five conceptual dimensions.
​

Fact table: FactEnsinoSuperior

Year

Country

Gender

Study Cycle

Field of Education

Number of Students

Conceptual dimensions (not necessarily materialised as separate tables):
​

DimYear (2013–2023)

DimCountry (European countries in scope)

DimGender (Male, Female)

DimStudyCycle (Short Cycle, Bachelor, Master, Doctorate)

DimFieldOfEducation (Eurostat/PORDATA categories)

Granularity is defined by the combination Year + Country + Gender + Study Cycle + Field of Education.
​

Results and Key Findings
The analyses show that European higher education is globally balanced between genders, with a slight female predominance over the entire period, approximately 54% women and 46% men, totalling around 390 million students between 2013 and 2023.

Moderate differences are observed across countries, with no extreme cases: countries like Sweden show higher female predominance (high GPI), while Germany and Greece present values slightly below parity but within a narrow margin.
​

The strongest asymmetries appear by field of education: there is higher female presence in Education, Health, Arts and Social Sciences, and higher male presence in ICT and Engineering, reflecting consolidated vocational patterns. At study cycle level, there is higher female participation in Bachelor and Master, near balance in the short cycle and a slight male predominance in Doctorates.

Overall, temporal trends are stable, with no abrupt breaks, indicating that gender participation patterns remained relatively constant over the decade, with only small annual variations. The dashboards allow these dynamics to be monitored and support moderate recommendations to promote greater diversity, especially in more imbalanced areas (ICT, Engineering, Education and Health).
